{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_downtown_ver02/data/sn83016244/00414180425/1945121301/0052.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nslre 2Cey West Citizen\nPublished Daily, Except Sunday, by\nL.. I*. AHTXAV, Owner and PuhlUher\nJOE ALLE\\, Rninri Manager\nFrom The Citizen Building\nCorner Greene and Ann Streets\nOnly Dally Newspaper in Key West and\nMonroe County\nEntered at Key West, Florida, as second class matter\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\ntse tor republication of all news dispatches credited\ntS* it or not otherwise credited in this paper and\nalso the local news published here.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne Year 110.00\nSix Months p-0o\nThree Months _ 2.75\nDne Month\nADVERTISING RATES\nMade known on application.\nSPECIAL, NOTICE\nAll reading notices, cards of thanks, resolutions\nof respect, obituary notices, poems, etc., will be\ncharged for at the rate of 10 cents a line.\nNotices for entertainment by churches from\nwhich a revenue is to be derived are 5 cents a line.\nThe Citizen is an open forum and invites dis\ncussion of public issues and subjects of local or\ngeneral interest- but it will not publish anonymous\n{ommunications.\nIMPROVEMENTS FOR KEY WEST\nADVOCATED BY THE CITIZEN\n1. More Hotels and Apartments.\n2. Beach and Bathing Pavilion,\n3. Airports\u2014Land and Sea.\n4. Consolidation of County and\nCity Governments,\n5. Community Auditorium.\nSCUTTLE AND RUN\nIt has been estimated that \u201cone billion\ndollars spent bvjhe government for relief\nof unemployment will produce approxi\nmately 500,000 jobs tor one year at \u00a72,000\neach. When the money is spent, nothing\npermanent has been added to purchasing\npower, and industry and the people are\nfaced with a tax burden to repay the bil\nlion dollars with interest. One billion dol\nlars invested tis risk capital will create the\nsame 500,000 jobs in the year in which in\nvested, but thereafter furnishes the tools\nfor 200,000 permanent jobs at a $5,000 in\nvestment per job. And those 200,000\npermanent jobs in industry wUI\nanother 100,000 in service\nindustries.\u201d\nIt \"should b# apparent Ljiat any*>p<ilH'y\nof government which destroys the forma\ntion of risk capital, or the desire of people\nto take business risks, is extremely short\nsighted.\nThe greatest incentive to risk capital\nis reasonable taxation under solvent gov\nernment. Recent tax reductions were in\ntended as an invitation to risk capital dur\ning the reconversion period. But the plain\nfact is that they are a fake invitation. If\ntaxes are to be successfully reduced, econ\nomy in government must accompany tax\ncuts. Tax reductions, countered by con\ntinued government borrowing, should de\nceive no one.\nToday we hear of plans for bigger and\nbigger government and lower and lower\ntaxes. One of the most respected observ\ners in America terms this type of action a\n\u201cscuttle and run\u201d policy. It is not con\nducive to the maximum activity of risk\ncapital.\nWHAT OF SMALL TOWNS?\n\nThe metropolitan area of New A\u2019ork\nis worried by what the publicists wall a\ncrime wave and Mayor LaGuardia has hp\npealed to Washington to release from mili\ntary service all former policemen of the\ngreat city.\nNow. here we have an illustration of\nhow things work in the republic. Because\nof its size the great city wants its police\nmen favored but what about hundreds of\nsmall municipalities who have ex-policemen\nin the armed services?\nDoes anyone imagine, for example,\nthat if Key West wished to get a former\npoliceman, or other official, released from\nservice to meet a local need that there\nwould be any prospect of persuading mili\ntary authorities to act, or that local leaders\nwould be going to Washington with such a\nrequest?\nThe size of New York multiplies its\nproblems but they are no greater, in rela\ntive degree, than the same problems in hun\ndreds of small towns and cities. In fact,\nthe probability is that the metropolis is bet\nter prepared to meet an emergency than\nthe smaller municipalities.\nWhen you buy Christmas Seals you\nhelp the war against tuberculosis and thus\nhumanity.\n\nIt may be heretical but we suspect\nthat the world would get along about as\nwell in the event that most of its \u201cleaders\u201d\nwere eliminated overnight.\nLAW IS SLOW BUT SURE\nThe layman often complains that law\nis snail-paced, and there is a great deal of\ntruth in that charge, but otfen the slowness\nis designed to assure certainty. That is al\nways true in the issuance of bonds that\ntaxpayers, eventually, will have to liqui\ndate.\nThat observation is made because\nsome Key Westers, anxious for us to have\na beach, appear to be impatient, now that\na majority of freeholders, who had quali\nfied by signing affidavits that they owned'\nrealty in Monroe, \"have voted in favor of\nbonds, and the impatience is due to the\nlegal procedure that now will have to\nbe taken before the bonds are validated,\nassuming that they are.\nReason for that action is because any\nbond-buying company insists on every as\nsurance, which means, in this case, a su\npreme court decision, or validation by a\negislative act, that the bonds can not be\nattacked as invalid at a later date, before\nit will purchase them for re-sale to its cus\ntomers.\nIn olher words, a company insists that\nthe bonds must be declared valid beyond\nquestion.\nAfter all. law, in the final analysis, is\ncommon sense, that is, common law, for\nmany a statutory enactment has been not\nonly unreasonable but ridiculous also.\nIn that category fall the so-called blue\nlaws, hundreds of which are still on statute\nbooks throughout the country, but no at\ntempt is mttde to enforce them. They died\nbecause they were not based on common\nsense but, as a rule, on an arbitrary attitude\nentertained by people who wanted to im\npose their views on their fellowmen.\nOl course, most statutory enactments\nare designed to promote or preserve our\nwellbeing.\nStatesmen seem to be making little\nprogres in making the world safe for atomic\nenergy.\nSTALIN\u2019S ROLE\nRussian Dictator Stalins failure to re\nftql'jil jSrptp a long and unexplained vacation\ncontinues to be the No. 1 mystrey in the\n.world\u201d Rumors\nwfs bad\u2018were discounted by United States\nAmbassador Harriman. after a Visit to the\nRussian ruler six weeks ago. It is now\ngenerally conceded there must be some oth\ner explanation for his absence from Mos\ncow.\nOne observer points out .Stajjjfs vaca\ntion began a efw days after Foreign Com\nmissar Molotov returned from the London\nconference, which ended when he took is\nsue with other foreign ministers over mat\nters preliminary to world peace. There\nare hints Stalin has walked out on his for\nmer allies, and will remain in retirement\nuntil they have something definite to offer\nfor a renewal of peace negotiations.\nThis means, of course, a program\nwhich completely satisfies the Soviet gov\nernment, and one under which it will profit\nto the fullest extent.\nAc cording to this version, Stalin is not\naccepting responsibility for the breakdown\nied pe&ce negotiations. His govern\nment has been represented by some of it*\nYounger diplomats, while he has assumed\nfhe role ol'adviser.\nPresumably, it the impasse continues\nindefinitely, he will step in and take charge\nof a situation in which others have failed,\nwith the object of increasing his stature at\nhome. Meanwhile peace must wait.\nThe man who waits for somebody else\nto do his work will wait to see his work\nundone.\nSTOP EROSION AT TTS START\nNearly every intelligent tiller of the\nsoil appreciates the importance of the fight\nagainst erosion. It is gratifying that a num\nber of our farmers have taken progressive\nmeasures to prevent surtace water from\nwashing away the valuable top-soil upon\nwhich fertility depends.\nNevertheless, there are many signs of\ndamage from erosion and it is perhaps well\nto urge all those connected with agricul\nture in Monroe County to be alert in the\nbattle against the forces of nature, whether\nthey arise from surface drainage on the\nfarm itself or from flood waters of sur\nrounding streams.\nIt would be a good idea for every ag\nriculturist to make a careful inspection of\nhis holdings for the purpose of spotting\nthe small washes that will become gullies\nand in time rob the land of its strength. A\nlittle precaution, at the right time, will save\nheavy loss in fertile soil and avoid more\nextensive efforts later on.\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nSPIRITUAL FOOD\nBy J. W. R.\nTHE BIRTH OF CHRIST\nAS TOLD IN LUKE\nThe story of the supernatural\nbirth of the Christ Child as re\nvealed in the Gospel according to\nSaint Luke (King James Version)\nis a beautiful story. The snnple\nwords that' unfold! \u00a3he divine\nevents may be -wndersfeoaci by a\nchild. IY\u00a3.. v.'sfttrv\ngrows 01d... a. story that 'stirs the\nheart gnrt sfctauhe mind to think\ning. In retelling in this column\nSaint Luke's inspired account of\nChrist's birth it is hoped someone\namong its readers will find an\nincentive for a spirtual reawak-,\nening.\nThe first chapter of Luke is de\nvoted to the revelation of visits\nby the Angel Gabriel unto Zach\narias. a priest, foretelling the\nbirth of John the Baptist who\npaved the way for the coming of\nthe King of Kings, and unto the\nVirgin Mary, foretelling the birth\nof the Christ Child. The chapter\nalso tells of Mary\u2019s Song to God\nthrough sheer joy of being chosen\nas the Messiah's mother: the birth\nof John the Baptist, and the se\nlection of his name in accordance\nwith instructions given by the\nAngel Gabriel.\n\nThe second chapter gives the\nnatiyity story and the Angel\u2019s\nSong. .jf is herp. \u2022-Styptual Food*'\nbegins unfolding for\u2019its readers\nthe simple truths '-trie Bible.\nOnly the first seven verses of\nthis chapter will be quoted today\nbut it is hoped the complete Bibli\ncal account of the divine nativity\nwill be published before Christ\nmas. The seven verses follow:\n\u2018\u201cAnd it came to pass in thoSe\ndays, that there went out a de\ncree from Caesar Augustus, that\nall the world should be taxed.\n(And this taxing was first made\nwhen Cyrenius was governor of\nSyria.) And all went to be taxed,\nevery one into his own city. And\nJoseph also went up from Galilee,\nout of the city of Nazareth, into\nJudea, unto the city of David,\nwhich is called Bethlehem: (be\ncause he was of the house and\nlineage of David:) to be taxed,\nwith Mary'bis espoused wife, be\ning. great with child.\n\u201cAnd so it was. that. While they\nwere there.' the da\\\u2018s were accom*\nplished that she should be dellv:\nered. And she brought forth her\nfirst-born sort, ahd wrapped hijry\nin swaddling clothes, and feud'\nhim in a manger; because thefe\nwas no room for them in the iruf.\n(To be continued.)\n-Today\u2019s Scripture Quotation;,\n\u201cHappy is; the man that\nwisdom, anetthe man that gettfcth,\nunderstanding.\u201d\u2014Proverbs 3:13.\nPOSSESSIONS SOLD\nHollywood.\u2014A ten thousand\ndollar custom built piano, other\nvaluable things which belonged\nto Rudolf Valentino, havb been\nput on the auction block. Juan\nRomero the owner of the former\nactor\u2019s home, has sold the_house\nto Ann Harding.\nSubscribe to Tne Citizen.\nLEGALS\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF THE\nELEVENTH JUDICIAL CIRCUIT\nOF THE STATE OF FLORIDA. IN\nAND FOR MONROE OOUNTY. IN\nCHANCERY. -T gn i\nCaw No. 10-500\n\u2014a .DIVORCE\nMiNNLE I.L'K GIBSON.\nDefendant. n\nORDER OF PUBLICATION\nTu: .Minni*- 1.. l,s>n\n:s*> Greenwich Park\nBoston. Massachusetts\nYou are hereby required to appear\nto the Bill for Divorce filed attainst\nyou in the above styled cause on\n\u2022>r before the 12th day *f January,\nA.IV. ISIS. otherwise the allegations\ncontained therein will be taken as\nconfessed.\nDone and Ordered at Key West.\nFlorida, this 12th dav of December,\nA. D. 1*45.\n(Circuit Court\nSeal) Ross C Sawyer\nClerk of Circuit Court.\nBy: Florence 